YelpCamp is a full-stack web application project that enables users to create and review campgrounds. To access certain features such as creating campgrounds or posting reviews, users must have an account.
                                     Key Features:
Public Access: Users can view campgrounds and reviews without the need to sign up or log in.
Authentication: Editing campground details or comments requires users to log in.
User Permissions: Users can only edit or delete campgrounds and comments that they have added.
Persistent Data: All data is stored securely in the Amazon Cloud.

                                     Technologies Used:
HTML5: Markup language for creating web pages and web applications.
CSS3: Used for styling and presentation of web pages.
Bootstrap: Front-end web framework for designing responsive websites and applications.
jQuery: JavaScript library for simplifying client-side scripting.
DOM Manipulation: Platform-neutral interface for dynamically accessing and updating document content.
Node.js: Cross-platform JavaScript runtime environment for executing server-side code.
Express.js: Web application framework for Node.js, facilitating the building of web apps and APIs.
REST: Architectural style for developing web services.
MongoDB: NoSQL database program for storing user information, campground details, and comments.
PassportJS: Authentication middleware for Node.js, offering flexibility and modularity for user authentication.
